column168: Description Of Events

THE SHIPMENT WAS BEING PROCESSED DURING THE OUTBOUND PACKAGE SORT WHEN THE LEAKAGE NOT NOTICED COMING FROM THE PACKAGE. THE ITEM WAS ISOLATED, OPENED AND EXAMINED TO REVEAL A PLASTIC INNER UNIT OF AN UNDETERMINED QUANTITY. APPARENTLY THE CAP SEAL ON THE UNIT FAILED ALLOWING THE RELEASE OF THE MATERIAL. THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED AND THE ITEM WAS PLACED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM. THE SHIPMENT WAS HELD PENDING NOTIFICATION TO THE SHIPPER FOR DISPOSITION.

ON 10-08-02 AT 0545 DOCKMEN WERE UNLOADING INBOUND UNIT 9062 WHICH ARRIVED FROM MEMPHIS, TN AT 0500 AND DISCOVERED 2 CTNS OF CORROSIVE LIQUID HAD BEEN PUNCTURED BY FORKLIFT BLADES WHILE BEING LOADED. THEY REPORTED IMMEDIATELY TO THE SUPERVISOR ON DUTY WHICH SECURED THE AREA AND FOLLOWED THE PROCEDURES STATED IN THE AAA COOPER HAZMAT CONTINGENCY PLAN (SPILL/RELEASE NOTIFICATION PLAN). EDDIE YANCE IN THE HDRM DPT WAS NOTIFIED AND INFORMED OF THE SITUATION AND HE GAVE INSTRUCTIONS ON THE PROCEDURES TO FOLLOW IN CLEANING UP THE SPILL.OIL DRY AND SODA ASH WAS APPLIED TO THE AREA WHERE SPILL OCCURED AND PAPER TOWELS WERE USED TO CLEAN RESIDUE OFF CARTONS CONTAMINATED. ALL CONTAMINATED ITEMS, PRODUCT, CARTONS, AND  CARDBOARD WERE PLACED IN HAZMAT RECOVERY DRUM TO BE DISPOSED OF AS REQUIRED BY THE FEDERAL DOT REGULATIONS. AAA COOPER HAD PROCEDURES IN PLACE TO DETERMINE WHO AND WHERE A SHIPMENT IS LOADED ON TRAILERS. AFTER DETERMINING THE PERSONS RESPONSIBLE FOR LOADING ERRORS THEY WILL RECEIVE A WRITTEN AWARENESS INTERVIEW, TRAINING (AAA COOPER DOCK TRAINING MANUAL) AND POSSIBLE DISCIPLINARY ACTION. AAA COOPER WILL CONTINUE TO PROVIDE THE TRAINING AND RESOURCES FOR EACH EMPLOYEE TO PERFORM THE REQUIRED TASKS IN A SAFE MANNER COMPLYING WITH ALL STATE, FEDERAL AND LOCAL LAWS OR REGULATIONS REGARDING TO SAFETY.

DRIVER CHECKED IN WITH CONSIGNEE AND WAS DIRECTED TO STORAGE TANK, HOSE CONNECTIONS WERE MADE AND CUSTOMER SIGNED OFF ON THE HOOK UP, DRIVER WAS PRESSURING THE LOAD OUT THE TRAILER AND WATCHING A SIGHT GLASS ON THE SIDE OF THE TANK WHEN THE DRIVER NOTICED THAT THE PRODUCT DID NOT APPEAR TO BE MOVING IN THE SIGHT GLASS ANY LONGER, DRIVER SHUT DOWN THE DELIVERY AND WENT TO THE BACK SIDE OF THE STORAGE TANK AND OBSERVED A VENT PIPE WITH PRODUCT COMING OUT OF IT INTO THE CONTAINMENT AREA. THE SPILL OF APPROXIMATELY 50 GALLON WAS CONTAINED, NEUTRALIZED WITH SODA ASH AND SHOVED OUT INTO DRUMS. CUSTOMER IS HANDLING DISPOSAL.STORAGE TANK DID NOT HAVE ENOUGH CAPACITY TO HOLD THE LOAD OF ACID THAT WAS ORDERED. VENT PIPE ON THE REAR OF THE STORAGE TANK PREVENTED DRIVER FROM BEING ABLE TO SEE THE SPILL ANY SOONER. DRIVER HAD ALL REQUIRED PAPERWORK SIGNED OFF PROPERLY PRIOR TO STARTING TO UNLOAD THE TRAILER. CUSTOMER NEEDS TO MAKE CERTAIN OF TANK CAPACITY WHEN ORDERING MATERIAL.

DRIVER STOPPED AT TRAVEL PLAZA FOR A MEAL STOP. UPON INSPECTION OF THE LOAD HE DISCOVERED A SMALL AMOUNT OF LIQUID ON FLOOR OF THE TRAILER. CLEAN HARBORS WAS DISPATCHED TO THE SCENE. IT TOO DID NOT MATCH UP WITH THE OUTSIDE PACKAGE ORIENTATION LABELS. SHIPMENT BEING SHIPPED UNDER Y610 WHICH ALLOWS UP TO 2 LITERS BUT THE INNER PACKAGES CAN NOT EXCEED 0.1 LITER OR 100 MI. AS THE 1 LITER EXCEEDED THIS AND THE FACT THAT THE INNER PACKAGES DID NOT MEET THE ORIENTATION REQUIREMENTS WE HELD THE PACKAGE AND NOTIFIED THE FAA/TSA OF THE DISCREPANCY. column168: ON FRIDAY OCTOBER 4, 2002 WHILE EN ROUTE TO MARISOL, INCORPORATED, MIDDLESEX, NEW JERSEY, APPROXIMATELY 3 GALLONS SPILLED WHEN A PRESSURE RELIEF GASKET GAVE WAY WHILE COMING TO A STOP ON THE SHOULDER OF ROUTE 202 NORTH IN FLEMINGTON, NEW JERSEY.  THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY CONTAINED THE MATERIAL AND CLEANED UP WITH ABSORBENT RAGS, PADS, SPEEDY-DRY AND SHOVEL. THE SPILL WAS THE RESULT OF MATERIAL LEFT IN OVERFLOW LINE, WHICH CAUSED THE PRESSURE RELIEF VALVE GASKET TO BREAK DOWN AND GIVE WAY.  THE MATERIAL LEFT IN OVERFLOW LINE WAS THE RESULT OF THE GENERATOR PROVIDING INACCURATE TANK CALCULATIONS TO THE DRIVER.

column168: OUR DRIVER THOUGHT THE TANKS AT THE SERVICE STATION WERE VAPOR MANIFOLDED AND THEY WERE NOT.  HE WAS DISPENSING PRODUCT INTO THE UNLEADED REGULAR UNDERGROUND STORAGE TANK WITH A COAXIL FITTING AND TRIED TO DISPENSE GAS IN THE PLUS TANK AT THE SAME TIME USING HIS 4" STRAIGHT DROP ELBOW THUS NOT ALLOWING THE TANK TO VENT WHEN HE REALIZED THAT THE PRODUCT STOPPED RUNNING.  HE THOUGHT THE COMPARTMENT ON THE TRAILER WAS EMPTY AND IT WAS ACTUALLY VAPOR LOCKED.  WHEN HE DISCONNECTED THE DELIVERY HOSE FROM THE TANKER UNLOADING HEAD, THE END PRESSURE IN THE UNDERGROUND STORAGE TANK BLEW THE GASOLINE THAT WAS LEFT IN THE DELIVERY HOSE ONTO THE GROUND CAUSING A 20-25 GALLONS SPILL.  DRIVER WILL CONFIRM THAT BEFORE DISPENSING FUEL THAT HE HAS AN UNDERSTANDING THAT THE UNDERGROUND STORAGE TANK IS EITHER MANIFOLDED OR NON MANIFOLDED.

INSURED COMPANY RESPONDED TO SCENE AND PUMPED REAR COMPARTMENT OFF ONTO ANOTHER TRAILER THEREFORE MINIMIZING THE SPILL TO 30 TO 40 GALLON.  LCM CORPORATION RESPONDED TO THE SCENE TO ADDRESS THE SPILLED DIESEL FUEL WHICH LEAKED ONTO THE ROADWAY.

column168: WHILE UNLOADING AT OUR LENEXA TERMINAL IT WAS NOTICED THAT THE DRUM WAS CORRODED AND HAD LEAKED. THE DRUM AND CLEAN UP MATERIAL WAS PLACED IN A RECOVERY DRUM. THE DRUM IS BEING HELD FOR DISPOSITION FROM SHIPPER.

DURING TRANSPORTATION TO OUR PARSONS LOCATION, 2 DRUMS LEAKED APPROX. 2 CUPS. THE SEALS ON THE DRUMS  WORKED ITSELF OUT FROM UNDER THE METAL BUNG RING AND DID  NOT FIT SECURELY CAUSING THE LEAKAGE. THE DRUMS AND CLEAN UP MATERIAL WAS PLACED IN A PLASTIC OVERPACKED CONTAINER. WE RECEIVED MSAS SHEETS FROM SHIPPER FOR PROPER DISPOSAL.

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: THIS REPORT WAS VERBALLY REPORTED IN ERROR AS THERE WAS NO INCIDENT AS A DIRECT RESULT OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS AS OUTLINED IN 171.15, 49CFR. THE VEHICLE WAS WESTBOUND WHEN THE RIGHT FRONT TIRE DROPPED OFF OF THE PAVEMENT ONTO THE WET, DIRT SHOULDER. THE DRIVER WAS UNABLE TO CORRECT. THE VEHICLE WAS PULLED FURTHER OFF OF THE ROADWAY UNTIL IT REACHED A DITCH THAT WAS APPROXIMATELY 24 INCHES DEEP CAUSING THE VEHICLE TO OVERTURN. LIQUID PRODUCT ENTERED INTO THE VAPOR RECOVERY LINE, IT IS STILL UNCLEAR HOW THIS HAPPENED. A SPILL OF APPROXIMATELY 2 TO 3 GALLONS OF GASOLINE OCCURRED ONLY AFTER THE VEHICLE WAS RIGHTED IN PREPARATION TO TOWING IT FROM THE SCENE.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED. WHILE UNLOADING AT THE BAX GLOBAL INC. FACILITY IN SWANTON, OHIO, A LEAK WAS DISCOVERED INSIDE THE TRAILER. UPON INSPECTION OF THE FREIGHT, BAX GLOBAL INC. PERSONNEL DISCOVERED ONE (1) 18.93 LITER STEEL DRUM HAD BEEN PUNCTURED BY ADJACENT FREIGHT. APPARENTLY, THE LOAD WAS IMPROPERLY SECURED WHICH CAUSED THE FREIGHT TO SHIFT IN TRANSIT. APPROXIMATELY 1/2 LITER WAS RELEASED INSIDE THE TRAILER. BAX GLOBAL INC. PERSONNEL PERFORMED THE CLEANUP WITH THE APPLICATION OF ABSORBENT MATERIAL TO THE FREE LIQUID. THE DAMAGED DRUM WAS PLACED INTO A SIXTY-GALLON SALVAGE DRUM ALONG WITH THE CLEANUP MATERIALS. THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT WILL BE HELD AT THE BAX GLOBAL INC. FACILITY PENDING DISPOSITION FROM THE SHIPPER. THERE WERE NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES REPORTED.

THE UNIT WAS IN TH E PROCESS OF UNLOADING. THE STAND THAT HOLDS THE UNLOADING HOSE IN PLACE BROKE, CAUSING THE SULFUR TO SPILL ONTO THE GROUND. THE DRIVER CLOSE THE INTERNAL VALVE AND STOPPED UNLOADING. A NEW STAND WILL BE BUILTED BY ROHM & AAAS DEER PARK TX.

column168: SIX OF SIX MANWAY COVER SECUREMENT BOLTS LOOSE, GATX 50696, OCTOBER 2, 2002 DETROIT DIVISION AT APPROXIMATELY 0850 HOURS, WEDNESDAY, OCTOBER 2, 2002 AT NORTH YARD IN DETROIT, MICHIGAN, A CONRAIL YARD CREW NOTED PRODUCT ON TOP OF TANK CAR GATX 50696 CONTAINING FERRIC CHLORIDE. APPROPRIATE NOTIFICATION MADE. A REPRESENTATIVE FROM PVS ARRIVED AT THE SITE, EXAMINED THE TANK CAR AND DETERMINED THERE WERE SIX LOOSE MANWAY COVER SECUREMENT BOLTS. PVS TIGHTENED THE MANWAY COVER SECUREMENT BOLTS AND CLEANED SPILLED AREA. CAUSE CODE 200 NARRI= 5(5+5+0)X(2+0)=100

column168: SHIPMENT OF VARIOUS LABORATORY TEST SUPPLIES WAS TENDERED IN SAN FRANCISCO, CA FOR SHIPMENT TO ROME, ITALY VIA CHICAGO O'HARE AIRPORT.  DURING CONNECTION FLIGHT TO ROME, AA EMPLOYEES IN CHICAGO NOTED THAT ONE COMPONENT OF THE SHIPMENT CONTAINED HYDROGEN PEROXIDE.  FOLLOW UP WITH THE SHIPPER/CHIRON CORP DETERMINED THAT THE HYDROGEN PEROXIDE SOLUTION WAS 30% WHICH WOULD REQUIRE DANGEROUS GOODS HANDLING IN MOST CASES.  THIS INFORMATION WAS NOT DETERMINED UNTIL AFTER THE AIRCRAFT HAD BEGUN IT'S TAXI.  THE CAPTAIN WAS INFORMED, AND THE AIRCRAFT RETURNED TO GATE WITHOUT INCIDENT.  THE SHIPMENT WAS UNLOADED AND RETURNED TO AMERICAN AIRLINES CARGO IN CHICAGO, FOR FAA FOLLOW-UP.  THE RESPONDING FAA AGENT LATER DETERMINED THAT THE SHIPMENT CONTAINED 1 MICROLITER OF SOLUTION.  THE SHIPMENT COULD HAVE BEEN SHIPPED WITHOUT DECLARING, AS LONG AS PROPER LABELING WAS AFFIXED TO OUTER CONTAINER, AND PROPERLY NOTED ON SHIPPER'S AIR WAY BILL.  THERE WERE NO INJURIES, DAMAGE, EVACUATIONS, OR RELEASE OF PRODUCT CAUSED BY THIS SHIPMENT.

column168: ON 10/16/02, A LEAK WAS NOTICED COMING FROM THE TRAILER PARKED AT THE SHEBOYGAN, WI FACILITY.  SUPERIOR SPECIAL SERVICES' SPILL RESPONSE TEAM WAS CALLED TO RESPOND TO THE SPILL.  THE SPILLED MATERIAL WAS NEUTRALIZED WITH SODA ASH AND CLEANED UP.  THE LEAK WAS THE RESULT OF 2 SMALL HOLES ON THE BOTTOM OF THE DRUM, POSSIBLY RESULTING FROM A NAIL IN THE PALLET ON WHICH THEY WERE BEING TRANSPORTED.
BATTERY WAS CASUALLY TOSSED ON TRAILER BY SHIPPER, CAUSING UNIT TO LEAK.
NO REMARKS

TRAILER ARRIVED AT DOCK AT 200 A.M.  WHEN THE DOOR WAS RAISED THERE WERE APPROXIMATELY 35 PAILS THROWN  ABOUT TRAILER. THERE WAS NO DUNNAGE AROUND PAILS NOR LOAD BAR TO HOLD PAILS IN PLACE DURING TRANSPORTATION. I CLOSED THE DOOR AND CALLED DAVE FOUGHTY REGIONAL SAFETY SUPERVISOR.

column168: OUR DRIVER WAS WESTBOUND ON US HWY 278, WHILE NEGOTIATING A CURVE THE VEHICLE LEFT THE ROADWAY ON THE RIGHT SHOULDER OVERTURNING AN UNDETERMINED NUMBER OF TIMES. THE DRIVER WAS EJECTED FROM THE VEHICLE KILLING HIM INSTANTLY. THE SPILLED PRODUCT WAS RECOVERED IN BOTH LIQUID FORM FROM HOLES DUG NEXT TO THE TANKER AND ALSO IN THE SOIL REMOVED FROM THE SITE AND IS BEING DISPOSED OF ACCORDING TO PRESCRIBED METHODS. IMMEDIATELY FOLLOWING THE ACCIDENT A 24 HOUR SAFETY STAND DOWN  WAS OBSERVED. ALL DRIVERS ATTENDED MEETINGS TO DISCUSS THE ACCIDENT, EVENTS LEADING UP TO  THE ACCIDENT AND PRECAUTIONS WHICH COULD HAVE POSSIBLY PREVENTED THE ACCIDENT FROM OCCURRING. ALL DRIVERS ARE BRIEFED ON A CONSTANT RE-CURRING BASIS ABOUT THE NEED TO COMMUNICATE WITH EACH OTHER ABOUT ROAD HAZARDS (I.E. UNFAMILIAR ROADS, ROAD CONSTRUCTION, ROADWAY OBSTACLE OR OTHER POSSIBLE HAZARDS).

column168: ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED. WHILE LOADING, ONE LEAKING FIFTY-FIVE GALLON PLASTIC DRUM WAS DISCOVERED. APPROXIMATELY TWO OUNCES OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED AND CONTAINED TO THE TOP OF THE DRUM. THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO A LOOSE BUNG. THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING AMPHOMAG AND GLOVES. THE CLEANUP MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO A FIVE GALLON PLASTIC RECOVERY DRUM, WHICH WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION. THE LOOSE BUNG ON THE DRUM WAS TIGHTENED AND IT WAS FORWARDED WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT TO THE CONSIGNEE. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED. WHILE LOADING, ONE CARTON CONTAINING TWO, TWO AND A HALF GALLON PLASTIC PAILS WAS PUNCTURED BY A FORKLIFT AT THE HALFWAY MARK OF THE TRAILER. UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT ONE PAIL WAS DAMAGED AND THE OTHER WAS UNAFFECTED. APPROXIMATELY TWO OUNCES OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED. THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING GLOVES AND ABSORBENTS. THE CLEANUP MATERIALS, WET CARTON AND DAMAGED PAIL WITH REMAINING PRODUCT WERE PLACED INTO ONE, FIVE GALLON STEEL RECOVERY DRUM. THE RECOVERY DRUM WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION. THE UNAFFECTED PAIL WAS REPACKAGED AND FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE ALONG WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED. WHILE UNLOADING, ONE DAMAGED CARTON CONTAINING FOUR, SEVEN POUND PLASTIC JUGS WAS DISCOVERED AT THE LAST-QUARTER OF THE TRAILER. UPON INVESTIGATION IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT TWO JUGS WERE DAMAGED AND THE REMAINING TWO JUGS WERE UNAFFECTED. APPROXIMATELY FOURTEEN POUNDS OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED. THE DAMAGE TO THE JUGS WAS DUE TO BEING CRUSHED BY HEAVY FREIGHT LOADED ON TOP. THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING LEVEL C PROTECTION, A BROOM, A SHOVEL AND AMPHOMAG. THE CLEANUP MATERIALS  WERE PLACED INTO ONE, FIVE GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM, ONE TEN GALLON METAL RECOVERY DRUM AND ONE, THIRTY GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM. ALL THREE DRUMS WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION. THE TWO UNAFFECTED JUGS WERE PLACED INTO A TEN GALLON METAL RECOVERY DRUM AND WILL HELD AT THE TERMINAL PENDING FURTHER INSTRUCTIONS. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED. WHILE UNLOADING, SIX, WET TWO HUNDRED AND FIFTY GALLON STEEL TOTES WERE DISCOVERED AT THE NOSE OF THE TRAILER. UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION IT WAS DETERMINED THAT TWO TOTES WERE LEAKING AND FOUR WERE AFFECTED. APPROXIMATELY FOUR OUNCES OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED AND CONTAINED INSIDE THE TRAILER. THE DAMAGE TO THE TOTES  WAS DUE TO LOOSE LIDS.  THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING GLOVES AND ABSORBENT PADS. THE CLEANUP MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO A FIVE GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM. THE RECOVERY DRUM WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION. THE TOTES WERE RECOUPED AND THE LIDS TIGHTENED TO PREVENT FURTHER RELEASE. THE TOTES WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL PENDING SHIPPER INSTRUCTIONS. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED. WHILE UNLOADING, ONE WET CARTON CONTAINING FOUR, ONE GALLON PLASTIC JUGS WAS DISCOVERED AT THE LAST QUARTER OF THE TRAILER. UPON INVESTIGATION IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT ONE JUG HAD LEAKED AND THE REMAINING THREE JUGS WERE UNAFFECTED. APPROXIMATELY THREE OUNCES OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED. THE RELEASE DUE TO THE CARTON BEING IMPROPERLY LOADED, CAUSING IT TO FALL TO THE TRAILER FLOOR AND THE CAP TO COME LOOSE. THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING GLOVES, TYVEK SUITS, BOOTIES, GOGGLES, A BROOM, A DUSTPAN AND AMPHOMAG. THE CLEANUP MATERIALS AND WET CARTON WERE PLACED INTO A TEN GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM WHICH WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION. THE CAP ON THE LEAKING JUG WAS TIGHTENED AND THE JUG WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL ALONG WITH THE THREE UNAFFECTED JUGS PENDING FURTHER INSTRUCTIONS. THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT WAS FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

column168: INFORMED THAT THERE WAS A HAZMAT SPILL AT APPROX 22:45 DOWN BY LEADMAN (RICHARD FISH).  I STARTED MY INVESTIGATION AFTER I EXPLAINED TO RICHARD TO SECURE THE AREA.  I RETRIEVED THE BILL, CHECKED THE ERG HANDBOOK, CHECKED ON THE INJURED EMPLOYEE, ROBERT WESTBROOK.  I EXPLAINED TO ROBERT TO RUN WATER OVER HIS ARM FOR AT LEAST 20 MINUTES.  AFTER GATHERING INFORMATION I WAS INFORMED THAT WHILE MOVING THE SKID THAT HAD THE CHEMICAL ON IT, A BOARD ON THE PALLET BROKE.  THE 20 GALLON CONTAINER ROCKED BACK AND FELL ON A NAIL ON THE BOTTOM OF THE SKID.  ROBERT SAW THIS AND LAID THE DRUM DOWN ON THE DOCK.  WHEN HE DID THIS SOME RESIDUE ON THE DRUM CAME IN CONTACT WITH HIS LEFT FOREARM. I THEN CALLED OUR EMERGENCY CONTACT PHONE NUMBER AND WAS TRANSFERRED TO EDDIE YANCE.  AFTER EXPLAINING EVERYTHING TO MR. YANCE, HE EXPLAINED THE PROCEDURES THAT WERE TO BE CARRIED OUT.  THEY WERE AS FOLLOWS 1. CONTACT CHEMTREC, GET MSDS AND SEE IF ANY MEDICAL ATTENTION WOULD BE NEEDED TO BE GIVEN TO ROBERT WESTBROOK.

column168: DRIVER WAS WEST BOUND ON I-10 AT MM 809 NEAR HANKAMER, TX, WHEN A RED CAR PASSED AND CUT SHARPLY BACK IN FRONT OF THE TRUCK. THE DRIVER SWERVED RIGHT TO KEEP FROM HITTING THE CAR, ONTO THE SHOULDER, THEN THE UNIT WENT ON OFF INTO THE DITCH ON THE RIGHT SIDE OF THE ROADWAY WHERE IT TURNED OVER ON IT'S RIGHT SIDE. THERE WERE 6-8 WITNESSES TO THE ACCIDENT, PER THE HIGHWAY PATROLMAN. NONE GOT THE LICENSE PLATE NUMBER ON THE CAR. PRODUCT LEAKED OUT FROM THE DOME LID INTO THE DITCH WITH STANDING RAIN WATER. LOAD WAS TRANSFERRED INTO ANOTHER TRAILER. SPILL WAS CLEANED UP BY CONTRACTOR (GARNER ENVIRONMENTAL) BY USE OF A VACUUM TRUCK. THE GROUND WATER AND SOIL WAS NEUTRALIZED.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: DRIVER WAS NORTHBOUND ON I-55 (4 LANE DIVIDED) IN HEAVY RAIN. HE ATTEMPTED TO TAKE THE EXIT RAMP EASTBOUND TO I-12. THE UNIT JACKNIFED ON THE WET PAVEMENT, SLIDING OFF INTO THE DITCH ON THE NORTH SIDE OF THE EXIT RAMP WHERE IT ROLLED OVER ON IT'S LEFT SIDE AND ALL THE WAY OVER COMING TO REST ON IT'S RIGHT SIDE. THE SPILL WAS THE RESULT OF THE VACUUM VENT ON TOP OF THE TRAILER, IN THE CRASH PROTECTION AREA, BEING PUSHED OVER. IT WAS PLACED IN A BIND PERMITTING THE PRODUCT TO RUN OUT. IT WAS PARTIALLY STOPPED BY PLACING ABSORBANT PADS AROUND THE LEAKING VALVE AND TRANSFERRING THE LOAD INTO ANOTHER CARGO TANK. CLEAN-UP CONTRACTOR (GARNER ENVIRONMENTAL) HANDLED THE CLEAN UP AND REMOVAL OF THE SPILLED PRODUCT AND CONTAMINATED SOIL.

CUSTOMER (CONSIGNEE) HAD DRIVER PULL SAMPLES OF PRODUCT AND LEAVE DOME LID OPEN WHILE CUSTOMER USED THEIR PUMP AND HOSE TO UNLOAD. AFTER A SHORT WHILE, CUSTOMER TOLD DRIVER TO PULL HIS TRUCK FORWARD A LITTLE. DRIVER DID SO WITHOUT HE, OR THE CUSTOMER PERSONNEL MAKING SURE THE LOAD WAS SECURE IN THE TRAILER. WHEN THE DRIVER STOPPED, AN ESTIMATED 15-20 GAL SLOSHED OUT OF THE OPEN DOME LID. DRIVER HAS RECEIVED INSTRUCTION TO NOT MOVE A UNIT UNLESS ALL THE OPENINGS ARE CLOSED AND SECURE.

RAILROAD EMPLOYEE NOTICED A HAZMAT TANK CAR LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET AREA OF CAR AND REPORTED IT TO THE TRAIN DISPATCHER.  THE DISPATCHER NOTIFIED EVERYONE ON THE HAZMAT INCIDENT CALL LIST INCLUDING THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT.  WHEN THE FIRE DEPARTMENT ARRIVED ON SCENE THEY PLACED A LARGE CONTAINER UNDER CAR TO CATCH DRIP.  THE ESTIMATED LEAK AT THIS TIME WAS LESS THAN 1/2 GALLON PER HOUR.  OUR CONTRACTOR TRANSLOADED COMMODITY INTO ANOTHER TANK CAR.  WE INFORMED THE FRA HAZMAT INSPECTOR THAT THIS WAS THE FOURTH INCIDENT WITH THIS COMMODITY, FROM DEFECTIVE EQUIPMENT, ON OUR RAILROAD SINCE NOVEMBER 2000.  THERE SEEMS TO BE A PROBLEM WITH THIS COMMODITY AND THE BOTTOM OUTLET FITTINGS AND GASKETS AREAS ON THE TANK CAR USED.  THIS HAS TO BE CORRECTED BEFORE THERE IS A MAJOR INCIDENT WITH THIS COMMODITY.

column62: Derailment; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: ON OCTOBER 12, 2002, SATURDAY, AT 1355 HOURS, M31971-12 DERAILED IN AMITE, LA. M31971-12 WAS NOTHBOUND ON THE MCCOMB SUBDIVISION AT MP#844.4. M331971-12 CONSISTED OF 2 ENGINES AND 117 RAILCARS, OF WHICH 106 LOADS, 4 EMPTIES AND 7 RESIDUE FOR A TOTAL OF 14415 TONS WITH A LENGTH OF 6, 711 FEET. ACCORDING TO THE CONSIST, RAILCARS NINETEEN(19) THROUGH FORTY-ONE (41) DERAILED FOR A TOTAL OF TWENTY-THREE(23). DURING THE SITE ASSESSMENTS IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT TWO RAILCARS HAD EITHER LOST THERE TOTAL CONTENTS OR WERE LEAKING. WITH THE ASSESSMENTS IT WAS DETERMINED THAT TWO OF THE PRODUCTS, HYDROCHLORIC ACID AND STYRENE MONOMER INHIBITED, WHEN MIXED CAUSE A VIOLENT REACTION THAT COULD RESULT IN FIRE. THE NORTH CUT OF THE TRAIN WAS REMOVED FROM THE SCENE, INCLUDING THE ONE DERAILED RAILCAR. THE SOUTH CUT OF THE TRAIN, 77 RAILCARS, WAS REMOVED FROM THE SITE. RE-RAILING OPERATIONS STARTED SUNDAY, OCTOBER 13, 2002 AT APPROXIMATELY 2200 HOURS. THIRTEEN OF THE RAILCARS AT THE DERAILMENT SITE WERE CLEARED. FOUR OF WHICH WERE RE-RAILED AND NINE WERE DRUG INTO A FIELD EAST OF THE SITE. ADDITIONAL SITE ASSESSMENTS WERE DONE TO DETERMINE THE BEST ORDER TO REMOVE THE REMAINING RAILCARS AND LIMIT EXPOSURE TO PERSONNEL. THE REMAINING NINE RAILCARS WERE REMOVED FROM THE SCENE. EIGHT OF WHICH WERE RE-RAILED AND THE NINTH WAS PLACED ON A FLATCAR. RE-RAILING PROCEDURES WERE COMPLETED ON TUESDAY, OCTOBER 15, 2002. REMEDIATION OF THE ROAD BED WAS CONDUCTED AND THE RAIL WAS REPLACED. THE RAIL WAS REOPENED AND THE FIRST TRAIN PASSED ON OCTOBER 15, 2002 AT 1500 HOURS. THE RAIL WAS OUT OF SERVICE FOR A TOTAL OF 75 HOURS (10 HOURS. 10/12/02, 24 HOURS. 10/13/02, 17 HOURS. 10/15/02). APPROXIMATELY 40 BUSINESSES WERE CLOSED DUE TO BEING IN THE EVACUATION ZONE. THE EVACUATION ZONE WAS REDUCED IN SEVERAL DIFFERENT STAGES. THE LAST OF THE EVACUATED RESIDENCE WERE ALLOWED TO RETURN TO THEIR HOME ON OCTOBER 15, 2002 AT 1800 HOURS.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Improper Preparation for Transportation
column168: ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED. WHILE LOADING, ONE CARDBOARD CARTON CONTAINING SIX, ONE GALLON GLASS BOTTLES WAS DAMAGED.  FURTHER INVESTIGATION DETERMINED THAT ONE BOTTLE WAS LEAKING AND THE REMAINING FIVE BOTTLES WERE AFFECTED.   APPROXIMATELY THREE-QUARTERS OF A GALLON OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED.  THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO HEAVY FREIGHT LOADED ON TOP.  THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING LEVEL C PROTECTION, AMPHO-MAG, A DUSTPAN AND BROOM.  THE CLEANUP MATERIALS, WET CARTON, AND LEAKING BOTTLE WERE PLACED INTO ONE, TEN GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM, WHICH WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION. THE FIVE AFFECTED BOTTLES WERE CLEANED OFF, REPACKAGED, AND FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED.  WHILE UNLOADING, FOUR WET FIFTY-FIVE GALLON STEEL DRUMS WERE DISCOVERED AT THE ONE-QUARTER MARK OF THE TRAILER.  APPROXIMATELY ONE HALF GALLON OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED AND CONTAINED INSIDE THE TRAILER.  THE DAMAGE TO THE DRUMS WAS DUE TO LOOSE BUNGS.  THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING ABSORBENT PADS AND GLOVES.  THE BARRELS WERE RECOUPED AND THE BUNG TIGHTENED TO PREVENT FURTHER RELEASE.  THE CLEANUP MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO A FIVE GALLON PLASTIC RECOVERY DRUM.  THE RECOVERY DRUM WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION.  THE DAMAGED BARRELS WERE FORWARDED WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT TO THE CONSIGNEE.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED.

column168: ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED.  WHILE UNLOADING AT A CUSTOMER'S FACILITY IN BATAVIA, ILLINOIS, THE TRAILER DOOR WAS OPENED AND ONE, FIFTY-FIVE GALLON FIBER DRUM FELL FROM THE REAR OF THE TRAILER AND STRUCK THE CEMENT DOCK, CAUSING THE LID TO POP OFF THE DRUM. APPROXIMATELY TWENTY-FIVE GALLONS OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED AND IMPACTED A DRAIN.  THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO THE DRUM BEING IMPROPERLY SECURED.  HAZMAT ONE OF OLATHE, KANSAS WAS CONTACTED TO COORDINATE CONTRACTOR RESPONSE.  HAZCHEM ENVIRONMENTAL CORPORATION OF ADDISON, ILLINOIS WAS DISPATCHED TO PERFORM THE CLEANUP.  HAZCHEM ENVIRONMENTAL CORPORATION PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING A HOT-PRESSURE WASHER AND A VACUUM TRUCK TO REMOVE THE FREE PRODUCT FROM THE DOCK AND THE AFFECTED DRAIN.  THE REMAINING PRODUCT INSIDE THE LEAKING DRUM WAS ALSO TRANSFERRED TO THE VACUUM TRUCK.  DISPOSAL WILL BE COORDINATED BY HAZCHEM ENVIRONMENTAL CORPORATION.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  ALL FEDERAL, STATE, AND LOCAL REGULATORY AUTHORITIES WERE NOTIFIED.

UPON TALKING WITH DSR JOHN HOLMES HE HAD SAID THAT THE PALLET WAS AT LEAST 5 TIERS HIGH AND WAS A VERY HEAVY PALLET, HE BELIEVES THAT THE CTNS THAT WERE PLACED ON THE TOP FEW TIERS MAY HAVE BEEN A LITTLE HEAVIER THAN THE BOTTOM ONES, WHICH CAUSED THE CTNS TO BE CRUSHED WHICH CAUSED THE ONE CTN TO RUPTURE AND START LEAKING. column168: WHILE PULLING AWAY FROM DOCK, TRUCK OPERATOR HAD A 55 GALLON DRUM ON THE TAIL END OF TRAILER THAT HAD NOT BEEN SECURED YET.  AS A RESULT, WHEN HE PULLED THE TRAILER AWAY FROM THE DOCK IT FELL OFF THE BACK OF THE TRAILER ONTO A DIRT MOUND ON  THE GROUND.  SUBSEQUENTLY THE IMPACT ON THE GROUND CAUSED THE TOP OF THE DRUM TO SLIGHTLY PUNCTURE SPILLING 1/2 GALLON OF THE CONTENTS ONTO THE DIRT MOUND.  DAMAGED DRUM WAS PLACED INTO A SALVAGE CONTAINER ALONG WITH THE DIRT THAT HAD ABSORBED THE SPILL.  THIS WHOLE INCIDENT COULD HAVE BEEN AVOIDED IF THE DRIVER HAD CHECKED TO INSURE THE DRUM WAS SECURE PRIOR TO PULLING THE TRUCK OUT FROM THE DOCK.

column168: WHILE MAKING A DELIVERY THE DRIVER NOTICED A CHEMICAL SMELL IN HIS TRAILER. UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION THE DRIVER DISCOVERED A DRUM OF M.E.K. THIS PARTICULAR SHIPMENT CONSISTED OF 5 GALLON PAILS THAT WERE STACKED THREE HIGH AND IN LOTS OF 36 PAILS PER PALLET.  EACH PALLET WAS STRETCHED WRAPPED AND BANDED TO SECURE THE PAILS TO THE PALLETS THAT THEY WERE STAGED ON.  WHEN OUR FORKLIFT OPERATOR WENT TO REMOVE ONE OF THE PALLETS FROM THE TRAILER THEY WERE IN, THE BANDING MATERIAL SLID DOWN CAUSING SOME OF THE PAILS ON THE TOP TIER TO SHIFT.  ONE OF THE PAILS THAT SHIFTED FELL FROM THE TOP TIER ONTO THE DOCK FLOOR CONSEQUENTLY CAUSING ONE TO SLIGHTLY CRACK AT THE TOP LID.  SPILLED MATERIAL WAS NEUTRALIZED AND CONTAINED WITH ABSORBENT AND PLACED INTO A RECOVERY CONTAINER ALONG WITH DAMAGED PAIL AND IS AWAITING FURTHER DISPOSITION.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: WESTBOUND RT 543 ON DOWN GRADE SLOWING TO 45 MPH PRIOR TO END OF GRADE I LET OFF THE BRAKE AS I WENT INTO THE LEFT BANKED CURVE STARTING UP HILL.  A DUMP TRUCK THAT WAS TRAVELING TOWARDS ME WITH HIGH BEAMS ON AND SEEMED TO BE MORE IN THE CENTER OF THE ROADWAY THAN I WAS, FOR A COUPLE OF SECONDS IT SEEMED TO BLIND ME, I FLASHED MY LIGHTS AT THE ON COMING VEHICLE BUT THEY FAILED TO TURN OFF THEIR HIGH BEAMS, AFRAID OF US SIDE SWIPING I MOVED OVER TO THE RIGHT SIDE OF THE ROADWAY BUT KNOWING THAT THIS ROAD HASN'T ANY ROOM FOR AN EMERGENCY MANEUVER I TRIED NOT TO GO OVER TOO FAR SO THAT I WOULDN'T CREATE ANY DAMAGE TO MY TRUCK AND TRAILER BUT IT SEEMS I MAY HAVE GONE TO FAR OVER.  AS I HEADED UP THE HILL EVERYTHING SEEMED TO BE OKAY UNTIL I REALIZED I MAY HAVE BEEN TOO CLOSE TO THE GUARD RAIL. column168: ON OCTOBER 23, 2002 OSCO, INC. HAD A TRUCK THAT WAS HEADED WEST BOUND ON 91ST STREET FROM ILLINOIS ROUTE 83, AT APPROXIMATELY 6:00 PM.  THE TRUCK MADE AN EVENTFUL STOP AT A STOP SIGN AT CLARENDON HILLS ROAD; THE NEXT INTERSECTION WAS AT CASS AVENUE 8 TENTHS OF A MILE AWAY, ON A 35 MILE PER HOUR STRAIGHT ROAD.  THE LAST 3 TENTH OF A MILE HAS A FAIRLY SIGNIFICANT DOWN GRADE.  THE DRIVER REPORTED THAT WHEN HE REACHED THE BEGINNING OF THE DOWN GRADE HE BEGAN TO APPLY PRESSURE TO THE BRAKES.  HE SAID THAT THERE WAS NO RESPONSE TO HIS BRAKING ATTEMPT SO HE BEGAN TO "PUMP" THE BRAKE PEDAL.  AS HE APPROACHED THE INTERSECTION WITH CASS AVENUE, (WHERE 91ST STREET DEAD ENDS) HE NOTICED A CAR APPROACHING THE INTERSECTION FROM THE SOUTH.  TO AVOID A COLLISION THE DRIVER ATTEMPTED TO MAKE A RIGHT HAND TURN, AT WHICH TIME THE VEHICLE TURNED ONTO ITS SIDE.  THE DRIVER REPORTED THAT THE OTHER VEHICLES SLOWED AND THEN CONTINUED NORTH ON CASS.  THERE ARE NO OTHER WITNESSES TO THE ACCIDENT OTHER THAN THE DRIVER OF THE TRUCK THAT WAS INVOLVED IN THE ACCIDENT.  THE DRIVER OF OUR VEHICLE WAS SENT FOR A DRUG AND ALCOHOL TEST, AND PASSED BOTH TESTS.  THE VEHICLE THAT WAS INVOLVED IN THE ACCIDENT LEFT OSCO'S YARD AT 13351 MAIN STREET AND STOPPED 5 TIMES PRIOR TO THE ACCIDENT WHICH OCCURRED ABOUT 10 MILES FROM OUR YARD. THE DRIVER REPORTED NO BRAKING PROBLEMS AT ANY OF THESE STOPS.  THE VEHICLE WAS INSPECTED BY A REPRESENTATIVE  OF THE ILLINOIS DEPARTMENT  OF TRANSPORTATION THE FOLLOWING DAY, AND REPORTED NO VIOLATIONS.  OSCO, INC. ALSO CONTACTED PACKER ENGINEERING (1950 NORTH WASHINGTON STREET, P.O. BOX 353, NAPERVILLE, ILLINOIS 60566-0353, 630-505-5722) TO INSPECT THE VEHICLE. THEY CONCLUDED THAT "BASED UPON THE EXAMINATION OF THE MACK TRUCK AS SUMMARIZED HEREIN, NO MECHANICAL DEFECTS WERE FOUND THAT CONTRIBUTED TO THE ACCIDENT ON OCTOBER 23, 2002."  THE VEHICLE THAT WAS INVOLVED IN THE ACCIDENT LEFT OUR YARD WITH 3800 GALLONS OF DIESEL FUEL IN THE TANK PORTION OF THE TRUCK.  THERE WAS NO FUEL LOSS FROM THE RUNNING TANK OF THE VEHICLE. THERE WAS SOME LEAKAGE FROM THE DOME COVER ON THE TANK PORTION OF THE TRUCK.  PRIOR TO THE TRUCK BEING UP RIGHTED, 3739 GALLONS OF DIESEL WAS METERED OFF THE TRUCK.  GIVING US A LOSS OF 61 GALLONS OF DIESEL FUEL.

column168: DURING A RIGHT HAND TURN AT THE CORNER FOLLOWING A STOP AT A TRAFFIC LIGHT, THE LEFT SIDE REAR TIRES OF THE CARGO TANK CAME OFF THE GROUND RESULTING IN THE TANK ROLLING ONTO ITS RIGHT SIDE.  THE RIGHT FRONT OF THE CARGO TANK IMPACTED THE CURBING CAUSING A SMALL PUNCTURE.  WITNESSES INDICATED THE SPEED OF THE VEHICLE AT BETWEEN 5 AND 10 MPH.  THE SPEED WAS APPARENTLY TO GREAT FOR THE CONDITIONS RESULTING IN THE ROLL OVER AND RELEASE.  THE DRIVER WAS INTERVIEWED TO DETERMINE CAUSE.  THERE WAS NO MECHANICAL FAILURE IDENTIFIED.  THIS ACCIDENT WAS THE SUBJECT OF A FLEET WIDE SAFETY MEETING. DISCUSSING THE NEED FOR DRIVER AWARENESS AND PROPER SPEED AND CONTROL AT THIS SPECIFIC INTERSECTION AS WELL AS DURING ALL TURNS.

ZEP MANUFACTURING WAS UNLOADING A TRAILER DURING HEAVY RAIN.  DUE TO THE HEAVY RAIN, THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER BEING UNLOADED HAD BECOME WET AND SLIPPERY.  A FORKLIFT SLID ON THE WET TRAILER BED INTO 2-55 GALLON DRUMS OF ZEP-ALUME (WHICH CONTAINS HYDROFLUORIC & SULFURIC ACID) AND PUNCTURED THE DRUMS WITH THE FORKLIFT TINES.  THE RESULTING INCIDENT RELEASED APPROXIMATELY 80 GALLONS OF PRODUCT INTO THE TRAILER BED, ONTO THE PARKING AREA, AND WAS SUBSEQUENTLY CARRIED AWAY BY THE HEAVY RAIN.  THE EMERGENCY RESPONSE COMPANY (GARNER ENVIRONMENTAL) CLEANED UP THE REMAINING PRODUCT, AND INVESTIGATED THE STORM-WATER RUNOFF SCENARIOS.  NO EVIDENCE OF LOW PH WAS DETECTED IN THE STORM-WATER RUNOFF SYSTEM, DUE TO EXCESSIVE RAINFALL. THE FACILITY HAS SUBSEQUENTLY INSTALLED AN AWNING OVER THE LOADING DOCK AREA TO PREVENT RAINWATER FROM ENTERING TRAILER'S, THUS PREVENTING SIMILAR INCIDENTS IN THE FUTURE.

column168: I, CHUCK WILSON HAD NOTICED A SMALL LEAK IN A TWO INCH STEEL NIPPLE COMING FROM THE LIQUID PUMP ON THE ANHYDROUS TRANSPORT (SEMI TRAILER).  I WAS ATTEMPTING TO FIX IT BEFORE THE REGULAR DRIVER REPORTED TO WORK. IN THE COURSE OF DISMANTLING THE PIPE A VALVE IN THE LINE MALFUNCTIONED CAUSING VAPOR TO RELEASE FROM THE DISMANTLED PIPE.  I HAD RELEASED THE PRESSURE ON THE LINE BY BLEEDING IT OFF INTO A WATER CONTAINER WE USE FOR THIS PURPOSE. THE INLINE VALVE SUDDENLY RELEASED ITS PRESSURE AND I WAS IN THE DIRECT LINE OF THE RELEASE.  NH3 VAPOR HIT MY BLUE JEANS ON MY LEFT THIGH BUT I DID NOT RECEIVE A BURN OF ANY KIND.  I HAD A PICKUP WITH TOOLS PARKED APPROX. 20 FEET AWAY TO THE WEST OF THE TRANSPORT.  WHEN THE VAPOR STARTED COMING OUT OF THE TRUCK IT FORMED A GROUND HUGGING CLOUD THAT ENVELOPED THE SEMI AND THE PICKUP MAKING MY CELL PHONES INACCESSIBLE. I RAN TO THE BUSINESS CLOSEST TO THE SITE.  SERVICE SUPPLY WAS OPEN AND I USED THEIR PHONE TO CALL 911.  I THEN RETURNED TO THE SCENE AND ASSISTED THE LOCAL FIRE DEPT. WHEN THEY ARRIVED MINUTES LATER.  THE FIRE DEPT. SET A PUMPER TRUCK UP SO AS TO PUT WATER ON THE SITE OF THE ESCAPING VAPOR AND ANOTHER WATER LINE FOGGING THE VAPOR CLOUD THAT WAS ESCAPING.  THE FIRE DEPT. ASSISTED IN GETTING THE MALFUNCTIONING VALVE UNDER CONTROL AND CONTINUED FOGGING THE AREA TILL THE TRUCK COULD BE SAFELY REMOVED TO AN ISOLATED SPOT AND DEPRESSURED SO IT COULD BE PROPERLY REPAIRED.  THE 911 CALL WAS RESPONDED TO BY THE SHERIFF'S DEPT.  THEY EVACUATED THE AREA EAST OF THE PLANT APPROX. ONE HALF MILE AND AN AREA OF TOWN WHEN  THE VAPOR CLOUD STARTED DRIFTING TOWARD IT.  SEVERAL BUSINESS LOCATIONS WERE EVACUATED FOR A SHORT PERIOD OF ABOUT ONE HOUR ALTHOUGH THE COURTHOUSE ANNEX EMPLOYEES WERE TOLD BY A DEPUTY TO STAY AWAY TIL NOON.  SCARE TACTICS WERE USED ON THE INDIVIDUALS AT THE COURTHOUSE ANNEX IN THAT THEY WERE TOLD THEY COULD BE GONE, LIKE THAT.  THE PUBLIC SCHOOLS WERE CALLED AND TOLD TO CLOSE THEIR WINDOWS AND NOT LET ANYONE GO OUTSIDE AT APPROX. 8:35 AM THEY WERE GIVEN THE CLEAR ABOUT 9:30 AM.  NO ONE WAS INJURED IN THE INCIDENT TO THE BEST OF OUR KNOWLEDGE.  REPORTERS FROM THE WESTERN BREEZE, PIONEER PRESS, AND THE GREAT FALLS TRIBUNE CONTACTED ME.  I TOLD EACH A VALVE HAD MALFUNCTIONED ON A TRUCK I WAS ATTEMPTING TO REPAIR AND THAT THE LOCAL FIRE AND SHERIFFS DEPT. DID A GREAT JOB OF HANDLING A POTENTIALLY DANGEROUS SITUATION.  I LEFT A MESSAGE ON JERRY WEINMEISTERS CELL PHONE THAT WE HAD AN INCIDENT AND WAITED FOR HIM TO CALL BACK NOT KNOWING HE WAS ON VACATION.  I CALLED MONTANA DEPT. OF ENVIRONMENTAL QUALITY AND SPOKE TO VICKI MARQUIS @ 406-444-3937.  I GAVE ROSS THAYER OUR GENERAL MANAGER A REPORT ON WHAT HAD HAPPENED AND WHAT HAD BEEN DONE AT ABOUT 4:30 TUES. AFTERNOON.  JERRY WEINMIESTER CONTACTED ME THURSDAY MORNING TO FILE THIS REPORT. I CONTACTED THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER THURSDAY OCT. 10TH.  INCIDENT #625607 LAST NAME THREATT.  I CONTACTED MT. DEQ THURSDAY AFTERNOON BUT NO NUMBER HAD YET BEEN

column168: ON OCTOBER 7, 2002 AT APPROXIMATELY 5:30 AM CDT, A D & D OIL COMPANY TRUCK AND GASOLINE TANKER WAS ENROUTE FROM ROME, GEORGIA TO MAKE A DELIVERY OF APPROXIMATELY 8,800 GALLONS OF UNLEADED GASOLINE TO COWBOY STORE #45 IN FORT PAYNE, ALABAMA. THE DRIVER OF THE TRUCK INDICATED THAT HE WAS TRAVELING ON HIGHWAY 9 AND BEGAN TO MAKE A RIGHT TURN ONTO HIGHWAY 35 WHEN THE TANKER OVERTURNED AND LANDED IN A FIELD AT THE NORTHWESTERN SIDE OF THE INTERSECTION. NO OTHER VEHICLES WERE INVOLVED IN THE ACCIDENT. THE ROADWAY WAS REPORTEDLY WET FROM A DRIZZLING RAIN AT THE TIME OF THE ACCIDENT AND FROM STRONGER RAIN EARLIER THAT MORNING. THE TANKER REMAINED INTACT EXTERNALLY; HOWEVER, INTERNALLY COMPARTMENT DIVIDING WALLS BREACHED ALLOWING FUEL TO ENTER VOID SPACES. THESE VOID SPACES ARE VENTED AND FUEL WAS LEAKING FROM ONE VENT OPENING. A PVC PLUG WAS USED TO STOP THE LEAK SHORTLY AFTER EMERGENCY CREW ARRIVED AT THE SCENE. FOAM WAS SPREAD OVER THE SOIL AREAS, AND A TRENCH WAS DUG AROUND THE TANKER. ADDITIONAL SOIL WAS BROUGHT IN TO CREATE A BERM INSIDE THE TRENCH AS A PRECAUTION. EMERGENCY PERSONNEL CUT THE FIVE COMPARTMENTS OF THE TANKER AND OFF-LOADED THE GASOLINE INTO ANOTHER TANKER. LESS THAN 200 GALLONS OF GASOLINE WAS RELEASED AT THE SITE. THE CONTAMINATED SOILS WERE EXCAVATED AND 83.81 TONS WERE REMOVED FOR DISPOSAL TO WASTE MANAGEMENT- THREE CORNER'S REGIONAL LANDFILL IN PIEDMONT, ALABAMA. COPIES OF THE MANIFESTS AND CERTIFICATES OF DISPOSAL FOR THE 83.81 TONS OF EXCAVATED SOILS ARE ATTACHED. THE EXCAVATION WAS BACKFILLED WITH SOIL FROM A NEARBY BORROW PIT. THE DISTURBED AREAS WERE GRADED TO APPROXIMATE THE PRE-EXISTING CONTOURS AND SEEDED.THE INCIDENT WAS REPORTED TO AEMA (ALABAMA EMERGENCY MANAGEMENT AGENCY). ADEM (ALABAMA DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGEMENT), AND NRC (NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER) WHICH ISSUED CASE NUMBER 625234

column168: APPROXIMATELY 70 GALLONS OF GASOLINE WAS RELEASED DURING THE DELIVERY OF GASOLINE TO AN UNDERGROUND STORAGE TANK AT A JOY FOODS STORE CONVENIENCE STORE.  THE FUEL WAS RELEASED ON THE ASPHALT-PAVED PARKING LOT AND THE PRODUCT FLOWED OVER THE PAVED SURFACE TO A STORM DRAIN, WHICH DISCHARGES TO AN UNNAMED TRIBUTARY OF POOR FORK.  POOR FORK IS A TRIBUTARY OF THE CUMBERLAND RIVER.  ENVIRO-PRO, INC. PERSONNEL PLACED ABSORBENT BOOM DOWNSTREAM FROM THE AFFECTED STORM DRAIN DISCHARGE ACROSS THE UNNAMED TRIBUTARY AND POOR FORK.  THE BOOM WAS MAINTAINED OVER THE NEXT FEW DAYS UNTIL NO SHEEN WAS OBSERVED.  IMPERIAL TRANSPORT INSTITUTED A PROGRAM THAT REQUIRES THAT DRIVERS REMAIN WITH A VEHICLE AT ALL TIMES DURING A DELIVERY.

column168: WESTBOUND #543 ON DOWN GRADE SLOWING TO 45 MPH PRIOR TO END OF GRADE I LET OFF THE BRAKE AS I WENT INTO THE LEFT BANKED CURVE STARTING UP HILL A DUMP TRUCK THAT WAS TRAVELING TOWARDS ME WITH HIGH BEAMS ON AND SEEMED TO BE MORE IN THE CENTER OF THE ROADWAY THAN I WAS, FOR A COUPLE OF SECONDS IT SEEMED TO BLIND ME, I FLASHED MY LIGHTS AT THE ON COMING VEHICLE BUT THEY FAILED TO TURN OFF THEIR HIGH BEAMS, AFRAID OF US SIDE SWIPING I MOVED OVER TO THE RIGHT SIDE OF THE ROADWAY BUT KNOWING THAT THIS ROAD HASN'T ANY ROOM FOR AN EMERGENCY MANEUVER I TRIED TO GO OVER TOO FAR SO THAT I WOULDN'T CREATE ANY DAMAGE TO MY TRUCK AND TRAILER BUT IT SEEMS I MAY HAVE GONE TOO FAR OVER.  AS I HEADED UP THE HILL EVERYTHING SEEMED TO BE OKAY UNTIL I REALIZED I MAY HAVE BEEN TO CLOSE TO THE GUARD RAIL.  I FELT A RUMBLE THROUGH THE RIGG BUT AT THAT TIME THE RIGG WAS TRAVELING STRAIGHT BUT SEEMED TO BY IT SELF STARTING TO HEAD FOR THE THREE LINE AND WHEN I FELT I NO LONGER HAD CONTROL I VIEWED THE PHONE POLL AND A LARGE TREE HEADING FOR THE DRIVERS SIDE SO I HELD ON TO THE STEERING WHEEL.  REMOVED MYSELF FROM THE DRIVERS SEAT AS IT HIT THE POLL AND FLIPPED IT STOPPED AND I ROLLED DOWN THE DRIVERS SIDE WINDOW AND CRAWLED OUT.  A&A ENVIRONMENT IS CLEANING UP THIS INCIDENT.

column168: BRANDON F RESPONDED TO A SPILL DON PPE UTILIZED DECISION TREE RESPONSE SHEET WHICH LED HIM TO CORROSIVE LIQUID.

THE SHIPMENT WAS BEING LOADED DURING THE OUTBOUND PACKAGE SORT.  UNKNOWN PERSON DROPPED THE PACKAGE AND THE LEAK OCCURRED.  THE PACKAGE WAS OPENED TO FIND THE METAL CAN CRIMPED AND THE BOTTOM SEAM LEAKED A LIQUID WITH A FLAMMABLE TYPE ODOR.  THE LABEL ON THE CAN CLEARLY INDICATED "SURFACTANT" WITH A LIST OF WARNINGS.  THE DG AGENT CONTACTED DG ADMINISTRATION TO REPORT THE SPILL.  AN MSDS WAS REQUESTED BY THE SHIPPER.  MSDS CLEARLY INDICATED A FLAMMABLE LIQUID WITH A FLASHPOINT OF 108.9F.  SHIPMENT IS BEING HELD PENDING FAA INVESTIGATION.  TELEPHONIC NOTIFICATION MADE TO AGENT BOB BRADY ON 10/15/2000 AT 2:30 PM AND UNDECLARED REPORT FAXED TO SAME AGENT 2:56PM.

SHIPMENT WAS BEING LOADED INTO THE VEHICLE WHEN THE LEAKAGE WAS DISCOVERED. PACKAGE WAS NOT MARKED DG.  PACKAGE WAS OPENED TO DISCOVER WHAT APPEARED TO BE A FLAMMABLE LIQUID WITH VERY STRONG ODOR.  SHIPPER COMPANY (PAM POSTUMA) WAS CONTACTED AND ADMITTED THAT THE ITEMS WERE FLAMMABLE AND FAXED MSDS TO FEDEX DG ADMINISTRATION.  COMPANY REP WAS NOT AWARE OF WHO SHIPPED THE ITEMS SINCE THIS COMPANY CONDUCTS PRODUCT DEMONSTRATIONS AROUND THE COUNTRY THROUGH INDIVIDUAL SALES REPS.. THE SALES REP WHO SHIPPED THE ITEMS FROM THE HOTEL DID NOT SHIP THEM AS DG. (SEE NAME ON AIRBILL).  THE COMPANY REP DID NOT CARE TO DISCUSS HOW THE PACKAGE FAILED THROUGH POOR PACKAGING OR DUE TO FEDEX FAULT.  SHE DID NOT SEEM CONCERNED THAT THEY HAD VIOLATED DOT REGULATIONS.

column168: CHICAGO HEIGHTS CAR INSPECTOR T. STEINBACK ADVISED THE DISPATCHER'S OFFICE AT 11:00 A.M. OF A LEAKING TANK ON THE BACK TRACK AT CHICAGO HEIGHTS. I WAS INFORMED OF THE INCIDENT AND WENT TO CHICAGO HEIGHTS. I ARRIVED AT CHICAGO HEIGHTS AT APPROXIMATELY 12:15 P.M. AND OBSERVED GATX 54887 DRIPPING TWO TO THREE DROPS PER MINUTE NEAR THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE. STEINBACK PLACED TWO BUCKETS UNDER THE DIPS TO CONTAIN THE SPILL. THIS CAR ARRIVED AT CHICAGO HEIGHTS AT 8:00 A.M. ON OCTOBER 27, 2002 LOADED WITH BUTYL ACRYLATES DESTINED FOR REICHOLD CHEMICALS IN MORRIS. BUTYL ACRYLATES IS A CLASS 3, PGIII, WITH PLACARDS OF 2348 AND A STCC CODE OF 4912215 I CONTACTED CHEMTREC AND WAS ADVISED THAT THE SHIPPER, BASF CORP., CONTACTED HMHTTC COMPANY FROM GARY, IN TO REPAIR THE CAR. THE REPAIR CREW ARRIVED AT 1:45 P.M. THE REPAIR CREW FOUND THAT AN OBLONG PLATE ATTACHED TO THE BOTTOM OF THE TANK WAS LEAKING FROM THE BOLTS THAT SECURED THIS PLATE TO THE TANK CAR.  THIS PLATE IS PART OF THE BOTTOM  OUTLET FIXTURE AND MEASURED APPROXIMATELY THREE FEET AT ITS LONGEST PONT. THE BOTTOM OUTLET FIXTURE IS ATTACHED TO THE TANK THROUGH THIS OBLONG PLATE AND CENTERED IN THE MIDDLE OF THIS PLATE. THE PLATE IS SECURED TO THE TANK BY EIGHT 7/8 INCH ALLEN BOLTS. THE LEAK WAS STOPPED AT 3:00 P.M. BY TIGHTENING FOUR OF THE BOLTS THAT WERE LOOSE. THREE BOTLS WERE TURNED APPROXIMATELY 1/8 OF AN INCH AND THE FOURTH BOLT WAS TIGHTENED APPROXIMATELY 1/4 OF INCH.  JOHN ANDERSON OF BASF ADVISED ME THE SEAL ON THIS CAR THAT SEALS THIS PLATE WAS REPLACED RECENTLY. THE CAR IS SAFE TO MOVE TO ITS DESTINATION IN NORMAL TRAIN HANDLING.

AT APPROXIMATELY 0745 HOURS (PST), OCTOBER 11, 2002 A CALL FROM THE APRIA HEALTHCARE HEALTHCARE BRANCH IN CLARE, MI. WAS RECEIVED. ARTHUR GALLAGHER(LOGISTICS SUPERVISOR) REPORTED THAT AT APPROXIMATELY 0930 HOURS(EST) AN APRIA VEHICLE WAS INVOLVED IN A MOTOR VEHICLE ACCIDENT IN HART, MI. AS A RESULT OF THE ACCIDENT THE VEHICLE OVERTURNED AN UNKNOWN NUMBER OF TIMES. THE APRIA VEHICLE CAME TO REST ON ITS PASSENGER SIDE. THE DRIVER OF BOTH THE APRIA TRUCK AND THE STRIKING VEHICLE WERE BEING TRANSPORTED TO A LOCAL HOSPITAL AND THAT THERE WAS A LEAK OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS, OXYGEN, REFRIGERATED LIQUID. THERE WERE NO FURTHER DETAILS AT THAT TIME. GALLAGHER WAS LEAVING TO RESPOND TO THE SCENE AND WOULD CALL BACK WITH ADDITIONAL DETAILS AS SOON AS POSSIBLE. AT APPROXIMATELY 0810 HOURS(PST) THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER WAS CONTACTED AND REPORT #625732 WAS FILED. AT APPROXIMATELY 1303 HOURS(PST) GALLAGHER RETURNED TO THE APRIA, CLARE, MI OFFICE. HE CALLED TO ADVISE THAT DELWYN TELLUS FUGERE, AN APRIA EMPLOYEE, WAS DRIVING AN APRIA OWNED 2001 ISUZU FRR, BOX TRUCK, SOUTHBOUND ON US 31, IN HART, MI WHEN IT WAS STRUCK IN THE REAR, CAUSING HIM TO LOSE CONTROL AND LEAVE THE ROADWAY WHERE THE VEHICLE OVERTURNED. THE STRIKING VEHICLE WAS A 1998 FORD, SEDAN DRIVEN BY NICOLE LYNN SABBY, OF FOUNTAIN, MI. AT SOME POINT DURING THE ROLLOVER OR WHILE THE TRUCK WAS RESTING ON ITS SIDE AN ESTIMATED 5 GALLONS OF OXYGEN, REFRIGERATED LIQUID ESCAPED FROM THE CRYOGENIC VESSEL(119 GALLON) THAT IS PERMANENTLY MOUNTED IN THE BOX, VIA THE PRESSURE VENT LINE. AT THE TIME OF THE ACCIDENT FUGERE WAS IN THE PROCESS OF GOING TO A VENDOR TO HAVE THE CRYOGENIC VESSEL FILLED. THE OXYGEN, REFRIGERATED LIQUID THAT ESCAPED EVAPORATED INTO THE ATOMOSPHERE AND THERE WAS NO CLEAN UP REQUIRED. MICHIGAN STATE POLICE TROOPER TATRO, #588, HANDLED THE ACCIDENT SCENE(REPORT #66-2448-02). BOTH DRIVERS WERE TRANSPORTED BY HART AMBULANCE TO LAKESHORE HOSPITAL FOR INJURIES RECEIVED IN THE ACCIDENT. THERE WERE NO INJURIES OR OTHER COLLATERAL DAMAGE AS A RESULT OF THE HAZMAT RELEASE. FUGERE HAD A LACERATION ON HIS FOREHEAD AND HIS EYES WERE SWOLLEN SHUT. HE WAS ADMITTED FOR OBSERVATION. JOHN, GENERAL YARD MASTER, STATED RAILCAR IC 151842 LOADED WITH CALCIUM CARBIDE WAS ON FIRE IN THE MIDDLE OF THE ALTON AND SOUTHERN YARD. JOHN REPORTED HULCHER SERVICES WERE TRANSLOADING THE RAILCAR EARLY IN THE DAY AND FIRE PERSONNEL WERE ON SCENE. JOHN MILLER, MANAGER ENVIRONMENTAL FIELD OPERATIONS, WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED. AT 02:02 AM, MGR. MILLER ADVISED THAT PERSONNEL FROM HULCHER WOULD RESPONDING TO ASSIST HIM WITH THE INCIDENT. MR. MILLER REPORTED THE INCIDENT OCCURRED WHEN HULCHER PERSONNEL WERE TRANSLOADING A RAILCAR AND STOPPED FOR THE DAY LEAVING PALLETS OF CALCIUM CARBIDE COVERED WITH A TARP. THE TARP BLEW OFF AND RAIN WATER ACCESSED THE EXPOSED PRODUCT CAUSING A CHEMICAL REACTION CREATING AN ACETYLENE GAS. THE ACETYLENE GAS THEN FOUND AN UNKNOWN HEAT SOURCE CAUSING THE PRODUCT TO IGNITE. AT 05:09 AM, MGR.MILLER DETERMINED THE CAUSE OF THE FIRE WAS DUE TO WATER ACCESSING CALCIUM CARBIDE THAT WAS OFF LOADED WHILE REPAIRS WERE MADE TO THE RAILCAR. MR. MILLER STATED THE PRODUCT WAS CONTAINED WITHIN FIVE GALLON METAL CONTAINERS, LOADED UPON PALLETS THAT WERE BROKEN DOWN FROM THE MECHANICAL DEFECT. MR. MILLER STATED THE MAJORITY OF THE FIRE WAS CONTAINED TO THE PALLETS AND PLASTIC TARPS. MR. MILLER ADVISED THAT THE FIRE BURNED ITSELF OUT AND THE SCENE WAS CLEARED.

column62: Inadequate Blocking and Bracing; Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails)
column168: DEAN COOPER, MANAGER OF CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, REPORTED CONTAINER CBHU 32837, CORROSIVE, WAS NOTED LEAKING AT THE ICTF, LONG BEACH, CA. THE CONTAINER WAS LOCATED IN E5, SPACE 295. INSPECTION NOTED LESS THAN ONE GALLON OF PRODUCT HAD DRIPPED TO THE PAVEMENT THROUGH THE FLOORING AND REAR DOORS OF THE CONTAINER. THE 20 FOOT CONTAINER WAS MOVED TO THE CUSTOMS DOCK TO CONTAIN AND ISOLATE PENDING AN INSPECTION. INTERIOR INSPECTION NOTED THE LADING TO BE 55 GALLON POLY DRUMS, DOUBLE STACKED, AND SECURED WITH TY-GARD. THE TY-GARD STRIPS WERE LOOSE ON BOTH TIERS OF DRUMS, WHICH ALLOWED THE ENTIRE LOAD TO SHIFT TO THE REAR. ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE WITH THE SHIPPER TO REMOVE AND INSPECT THE DRUMS. WHILE REMOVING THE TOP TIER DRUMS, NOTED A SINGLE STRIP OF TY-GARD HAD BEEN INSTALLED AT MID SHIP TO BAY OUT THE LADING. THIS STRIP WAS ALSO LOOSE. MANUFACTURERS APPLICATION REQUIRES THE USE OF TWO STRIPS OF TY-GARD TO PROPERLY SECURE THE LADING. ALSO NOTED, THE SHIPPER ONLY USED TWO FULL SHEETS OF 3/4 INCH PLYWOOD FOR THE BI-LEVEL SEPARATION. THE REMAINDER OF THE BI-LEVEL SEPARATION WAS TWO FOOT WIDE CUT SECTIONS OF 1/4 INCH PLYWOOD, WHICH WAS OVERLAPPING, CAUSING AN UNEVEN SURFACE FOR THE TOP TIER DRUMS TO REST UPON. THIS IS A CONTRIBUTING FACTOR TO THE LADING MOVING DURING TRANSIT. WHILE REMOVING THE DRUMS FROM THE FLOOR TIER, LOCATED ONE DRUM, THREE ROWS IN FROM THE REAR DOORS, ON THE RIGHT SIDE, WHICH HAD SHIFTED TO THE REAR AND IMPACTED A NAIL ON THE FLOORING. THE NAIL CONTACTED THE BOTTOM OUTSIDE EDGE OF THE DRUM AND WORE THROUGH THE POLY DRUM. THE DRUM COMPACTED FROM THE NEGATIVE VAPOR AREA AS THE LIQUID ESCAPED. APPROXIMATELY 25 GALLONS OF PRODUCT WAS LOST, INDICATING IT HAD BEEN LEAKING FOR SOME TIME. SEVERAL DRUMS WERE NOTED TO HAVE AN OUNCE OR TWO OF PRODUCT POOLED AROUND THE BUNGS. IT IS NOT KNOWN IF THE PRODUCT ESCAPED FROM THE BUNGS, AS THE BUNGS WERE REASONABLY TIGHT. IT IS SUSPECTED THE PRODUCT POOLED AROUND THE BUNGS PRODUCED A VAPOR THAT ATTACKS THE ADHESIVE USED WITH THE TY-GARD MATERIAL, WHICH MAY HAVE BEEN A CONTRIBUTING FACTOR TO THE TY-GARD COMING LOOSE DURING TRANSIT. THE DAMAGED DRUM WAS PATCHED AND PLACED INTO A POLY SALVAGE DRUM FOR SECUREMENT. THE CONTAINER WAS CLEANED OF THE RESIDUE PRODUCT AND THE FLOOR REINSPECTED. TWO ADDITIONAL NAILS WERE LOCATED AND REMOVED FROM THE FLOORING. ALL OF THE DRUMS WERE PLACED BACK INTO TO ORIGINAL CONTAINER AND BLOCKED AND BRACED FOR MOVEMENT ONTO THE HARBOR FOR VESSEL LOADING. THE DAMAGED DRUM TO BE RETURNED TO THE MANUFACTURER PER THEIR REQUEST.

DEAN COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED. DEVELOPED APPROXIMATELY 100 PLUS GALLONS OF PRODUCT WAS LEAKED FROM A 275 GALLON TOTE WITHIN THE CONTAINER. THE CONTAINER HAD BEEN PICKED UP BY AN OUTSIDE DRIVER, AND WAS NOTED LEAKING AT THE GATE, THEN SET BACK TO THE HOLDING LOT. TRANSLOADING ENVIRONMENTAL WAS CONTACTED AND REQUESTED TO RESPOND. APPROXIMATELY 200 GALLONS OF THE PRODUCT LEAKED FROM THE TOTE, ONTO THE PAVEMENT. THE AREA WAS DIKED TO CONTAIN THE RELEASE, WITH THE FREE PRODUCT ABSORBED AND SWEPT UP. APPROXIMATELY 75 GALLONS OF PRODUCT WAS REMOVED FROM THE TOTE AND PLACED INTO DRUMS. INSPECTION OF THE TOTE NOTED THE 1/2 INCH TUBE CAGE AROUND THE POLY TOTE HAD BROKEN NEAR THE BOTTOM SIDE OF THE TOTE. IT IS SUSPECTED THE DRAYMAN WENT OVER ONE OF THE SPEED BUMPS IN THE YARD AT AN EXECESSIVE SPEED, CAUSING THE LIQUID IN THE TOTE TO SURGE AND BOW THE SIDES OF THE POLY TOTE. WITH THE TUBE CAGE ALREADY BROKEN IN TWO PLACES, THE SIDES BOWED, COMING INTO CONTACT WITH THE JAGGED EDGE OF THE TUBING, PUNCTURING THE SIDE WALL. AS THE PRODUCT ESCAPED, THE TOTE COLLAPSED ONTO ITSELF. INSPECTION OF THE INTITIAL PARKING SLOT SHOWED NO SIGNS OF ANY PRODUCT LEAKAGE. THE ONLY PRODUCT ON THE GROUND WAS AT THE INSPECTION GATE AND THE PARKING SLOT IN RED LOT WHERE THE DRIVER MOVED THE CONTAINER AFTER IT WAS NOTED LEAKING. ANOTHER FACTOR IN THE TOTE FAILURE WAS THE WAY IT WAS STOWED WITHIN THE CONTAINER. THIS TOTE WAS AT THE REAR OF THE LOAD, OFF SET BY ITSELF, RESTING AGAINST THE RIGHT REAR SIDE WALL OF THE CONTAINER. IT WAS ONLY HELD IN PLACE WITH TWO PIECES OF CUT 2X4 NAILED TO THE FLOOR. THERE WAS NO OTHER SUPPORT TO THREE SIDES OF THIS TOTE. WITH THE LIGHT POLY TOTE, LIQUID SURGE WITHIN THE TOTE, AND THE FLIMSY 1/2 TUBE CAGE, ALL FACTORS COMBINED TOGETHER, ALLOWED THE TOTE TO FLEX DURING TRANSIT, CAUSING THE CAGE TO BREAK, AND THE TOTE TO BE PUNCTURED. THE CONTAINER WAS CLEANED OF THE RESIDUE, AND THE FREIGHT PLACED BACK INTO THE ORIGINAL CONTAINER. ONCE THE LADING WAS PROPERLY BLOCKED AND BRACED, THE CONTAINER WAS RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT ONTO THE LOCAL CONSIGNEE.

AT 1815HRS ON 10-19-02, CTS MGR LERCH WAS ADVISED BY THE RMCC THAT MANAGER YARD OPERATIONS PAUL CROCKER HAD REPORTED TANK CAR TIMX 201064 TO BE LEAKING FROM THE TOP OF THE CAR. HE FURTHER ADVISED CAR WAS LOCATED IN TRACK 303, LIVONIA, LA., AND WAS LEAKING AT A RATE OF APPROXIMATELY ONE GALLON HOUR. CAR WAS IMMEDIATELY ISOLATED IN THE HAZARDOUS MATERIALS TRACK FOR SAFETY AND FURTHER HANDLING. AT 2035HRS U.S. ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES ARRIVED ON SCENE AND UPON THEIR INSPECTION, PRODUCT WAS NOTED TO BE LEAKING FROM THE FOUR BOLT FLANGE TO THE THREE INCH LIQUID VALVE. THREE NUTS WERE FOUND TO BE LOOSE ONE TURN, AND ONE NUT WAS FOUND TO BE HAND TIGHT. UPON TIGHTENING OF THE FOUR NUTS, THE CAR WAS SECURED FROM FURTHER RELEASE OF PRODUCT. THE CAR AND AFFECTED AREAS WERE RINSED WITH A NEUTRALIZING SOLUTION, AND THE AREA CLEARED AT APPROXIMATELY 2300HRS. THERE WERE NO DRAINS OR WATERWAYS IMPACTED OR REPORTED INJURIES RESULTING FROM THIS RELEASE.

ERIC, TRIAN DISPATCHER 26, REPORTED VIA AVTEC, TRAIN MFWOD 22, UP 6363, DERAILED AT MP 498, EAST OF COAHOMA. ERIC REPORTED A POSSIBLE TWELVE RAILCARS DERAILED, CAR NUMBERS AND CONTENTS UNKNOWN. ERIC ADVISED THE CONDUCTOR HAD NOT YET WALKED BACK. THIS TRAIN HAS A TOTAL OF FIFTY-SIX RAILCARS, THIRTY-ONE LOADS AND TWENTY-FIVE EMPTIES. THERE ARE SEVERAL HAZARDOUS MATERIAL CARS, BOTH LOADS AND RESIDUE EMPTIES WITHIN THE TRAIN. THERE WERE NO REPORTED INJURIES AND THE CAUSE HAS NOT BEEN DETERMINED. MIKE KELLY, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY MANAGER, WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED. AT 01:18 PM MGR. MIKE KELLY REPORTED HE HAD DISPATCHED EAGLE ENVIRONMENTAL AND BNC ENVIRONMENTAL. MR. KELLY ALSO REQUESTED THAT RMCC CONTACT CTEH. AT 01:19 PM RMCC CONTACTED CHERRI, HOWARD COUNTY SHERIFFS OFFICE. CHERRI REPORTED LOCAL RESPONDERS WERE ON SCENE AND TWO TANKCARS WERE LEAKING HYDROCHLORIC ACID. THERE WERE NO INJURIES OR EVACUATIONS REPORTED. THERE WAS A WHITE VAPOR AND LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS ON THE SCENE. INSPECTION OF THE DERAILMENT SITE DETERMINED THAT TANKCAR GATX 72835 WAS PUNCTURED BY ANOTHER RAILCAR AND LEAKED 4,000 GALLONS OF HYDROCHLORIC ACID. TANKCAR RCRX 1512 WAS UPSIDE DOWN AND RELEASED APPROXIMATELY 200 GALLONS OF HYDROCHLORIC ACID. A LIME SLURRY SOLUTION WAS USED TO NEUTRALIZE THE SPILLED PRODUCT. TANKCAR RCRX 1512 WAS LATER TRANSFERRED TO TANK TRUCKS.

column62: Derailment; Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Rollover Accident
column168: ON THE AFTERNOON OF WEDNESDAY, 10/23/02 THE UNION PACIFIC RAILROAD TRAIN "LLS03-23" WAS SHOVING A CUT OF CARS AROUND THE CURVE OF THE AMPRO LEAD WHEN THE HIGH RAIL ROLLED OUT AND DERAILED TEN CARS. SIX CARS REMAINED UPRIGHT WHILE FOUR CARS ROLLED OVER ONTO THEIR SIDES. INCLUDED IN THE DERAILED CARS ON THEIR SIDES WAS TANK CAR GATX 94449. NOTIFICATION WAS MADE TO THE UPRR RISK MANAGEMENT COMMUNICATIONS CENTER. RMCC SUBSEQUENTLY CONTACTED UPRR MANAGER ENVIRONMENTAL FIELD OPERATIONS, T.M. ROBINSON. ROBINSON RESPONDED AND ALONG WITH THE RESPONDERS FROM THE LOUISIANA STATE POLICE, THE LOUISIANA DEPT. OF ENVIRONMENTAL QUALITY, ASCENSION PARISH SHERIFF'S OFFICE, TRIAD NITROGEN AND CF INDUSTRIES INSPECTED THE DERAILED CARS INCLUDING GATX 94449. ROBINSON WAS INFORMED BY MR. RICHARD BARTLEY OF TRIAD OWNED THE LEAD TRACK AND WOULD BE RESPONSIBLE FOR THE INCIDENT. IT WAS INITIALLY DETERMINED THAT THERE HAD NOT BEEN ANY RELEASE OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS AND THAT THE ONLY SPILLAGE WAS SEVERAL HUNDRED POUNDS OF (DRY) UREA FROM HOPPER CAR CRLE 539037. A WORK CREW FROM EAGLE CONSTRUCTION & ENVIRONMENTAL WAS ASSIGNED TO COVER THE SPILLED UREA WITH PLASTIC UNTIL IT COULD BE RECOVERED BY VACUMM TRUCKS. AT ABOUT 2030 HOURS MR. MIKE TODD OF EAGLE REPORTED THAT TANK CAR GATX 94449 WAS LEAKING ANHYDROUS AMMONIA FROM WITHIN THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING. THE INCIDENT COMMANDER, LSP TROOPER L.L. LEWIS, AUTHORIZED AN ENTRY TEAM TO INSPECT AND ASSESS THE LOCATION AND EXTENT OF THE LEAK AND SECURE SAME IF POSSIBLE. THE ENTRY TEAM CONSISTED OF LSP TROOPER TERRY PATE, MR. RICHARD BARTLEY AND MR. DON LEBLANC OF TRIAD AND ROBINSON. THE TEAM FOUND THAT LIQUID AMMONIA WAS DRIPPING FROM THE PACKING GLAND NUT ON THE SLIP TUBE GAGING DEVICE. BARTLEY, USING A PAIR OF CHANNEL LOCK PLIERS WAS ABLE TO TIGHTEN THE NUT APPROXIMATELY ONE AND ONE HALF TURNS AND THIS SECURED THE LEAK. ALL OF THE CARS WERE RERAILED BY HULCHER SERVICES THE NEXT DAY WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT AND RETURNED TO THE PLANT FOR UNLOADING AND REPAIR AS NEEDED.

ANETTE, MANAGER OF YARD OPERATIONS, REPORTED A SWEET SMELLING ODOR EMANATING FROM TANKCAR SCMX 4302 LOCATED ON TRACK 13 IN THE ANGLETON YARD. TIM O'BRIEN, REGIONAL MANAGER OF CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED. AT 03:40 AM. REGIONAL MANAGER O'BRIEN REPORTED ALL EIGHT SWING BOLTS ON THE MANWAY COVER WERE LOOSE. MR. O'BRIEN TIGHTENED THE BOLTS AND RELEASED THE TANKCAR TO DESTINATION.

JIM SWEENEY, GATE AGENT, REPORTED AN UNKNOWN AMOUNT OF LIQUID WAS NOTED DRIPPING FROM CONTAINER TRLU 584657, CURRENTLY LOCATED AT THE CITY OF INDUSTRY INTERMODAL YARD. DEAN COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS NOTIFIED AND EN ROUTE. THE CONTAINER WAS MOVED TO THE HAZMAT CONTAINMENT AREA, WHERE IT COULD BE ISOLATED PENDING INSPECTION. INSPECTION OF THE LADING NOTED THE CONTENTS TO BE ZEP CLEANING PRODUCTS. BLOCKING AND BRACING WAS NOT TO AAR BOE 6C STANDARD. NEAR THE REAR OF THE LOAD, LOCATED TWO PALLETS, WHICH HAD SIX EACH, 20 GALLON DRUMS. THE DRUMS APPEARED TO BE THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK. TRANSLOADING ENVIRONMENTAL WAS REQUESTED TO RESPOND WITH A TEAM TO REWORK THE LADING. ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE WITH APL, THE SHIPPER OF RECORD, TO REMOVE THE LADING TO DEVELOP THE SOURCE OF THE LEAKAGE. THE TWO PALLETS CONTAINING THE 20 GALLON DRUMS, ONE STACKED ON TOP OF THE OTHER WITH NO BI-LEVEL SEPARATION, WERE REMOVED AND INSPECTED. TWO OF THE DRUMS FROM THE FLOOR LOADED PALLET HAD SEVER FLAT SPOTS ON THE BOTTOM AREA OF THE BOTTOM CHIMES, WHICH DEVELOPED STRESS CRACKS, ALLOWING THE ENTIRE CONTENTS OF THE DRUMS TO LEAK OUT DURING TRANSIT. TWO MORE DRUMS HAD FLAT SPOTS ON THE BOTTOM AREA OF THE BOTTOM CHIMES, HOWEVER, DID NOT LEAK. THE REMAINING TWO DRUMS SHOWED NO SIGNS OF DAMAGE. THERE WERE NO INDICATORS ON THE PALLET TO WARRENT THIS TYPE OF DAMAGE TO THE BOTTOM CHIMES, AND IT IS SUSPECTED THE DRUMS WERE DAMAGED PRIOR TO LOADING AT THE POINT OF ORIGIN. THE DRUM CONTENTS WERE MARKED AS ID RED, A FLAMMABLE LIQUID DEGREASER. ESTIMATED A TOTAL OF 40 GALLONS OF THE PRODUCT WAS LOST WHILE IN TRANSIT. THE DAMAGED AND LEAKING DRUMS WERE PATCHED AND PLACED INTO SALVAGE DRUMS FOR SECUREMENT. THE CONTAINER WAS CLEANED OF THE RESIDUE, AND THE LADING PLACED BACK INTO THE ORIGINAL CONTAINER. THE SALVAGE DRUMS WERE ALSO PLACED BACK INTO THE LOAD PER THE REQUEST OF THE SHIPPER, AS THE CONTAINER WAS DESTINED FOR LOCAL DELIVERY.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails)
column168: THOMAS, ICTF SECURITY, REPORTED AN UNKNOWN AMOUNT OF CORROSIVE LIQUID HAD BEEN RELEASED ONTO RAILCAR BNSC 212188, FROM CONTAINER KKTU 716152, CURRENTLY LOCATED AT THE B SECTION OF TRACK 811, IN THE ICTF INTERMODAL YARD, LONG BEACH, CA.  A SMALL SPOT OF PRODUCT, LESS THAN ONE GALLON HAD POOLED AT THE END OF THE DOUBLE STACK CAR.  THE ABOVE CONTAINER WAS MOVED TO THE CUSTOMS DOCK WHERE IT COULD BE ISOLATED PENDING INSPECTION.  DEAN COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED.  INSPECTION DEVELOPED 76 CLOSED HEAD METAL DRUMS, DOUBLE STACKED WITHIN THE CONTAINER.  WHILE BLOCKING AND BRACING WAS NOT TO AAR BOE6C STANDARD, IT APPEARED ADEQUATE TO RESTRAIN THE LADING.  IT WAS NOTED CUT STRIPS OF 1/4 INCH PLYWOOD WAS USED FOR BI-LEVEL SEPARATION, WHICH IS NOT TO STANDARD.  ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE WITH THE SHIPPER TO REMOVE THE DRUMS AND INSPECT THEM FOR DAMAGE AND/OR LEAKAGE.  TWO DRUMS WERE LOCATED IN THE TOP TIER, FRONT ROW, AT THE LEFT FRONT NOSE CORNER, THAT APPEARED TO BE LEAKING.  ONE DRUM HAD A TWO INCH FLAT SPOT ON THE BOTTOM PORTION OF THE BOTTOM CHIME, WHICH HAD A 1/4 INCH GOUGE, ALLOWING PRODUCT TO ESCAPE.  AS THIS DRUM WAS LOCATED ON THE TOP TIER, WITH NO VISIBLE OBSTRUCTIONS ON THE PLYWOOD, IT IS SUSPECTED THE CHIME WAS DAMAGED PRIOR TO OR DURING THE LOADING PROCESS.  THE SECOND DRUM HAD PRODUCT WEEPING PAST THE BOTTOM CHIME INITIALLY, HOWEVER, AFTER ALLOWING THE DRUM TO SIT OVERNIGHT, ALL ADDITIONAL ATTEMPTS TO MAKE THE DRUM LEAK FAILED.  BOTH DRUMS WERE PLACED INTO SALVAGE DRUMS AND SECURED.  TWO ADDITIONAL DRUMS HAD SUFFICIENT DAMAGE NOTED THAT THEY WERE DEEMED UNFIT FOR FURTHER TRANSIT.  THESE WERE ALSO PLACED INTO SALVAGE DRUMS FOR SECUREMENT.  THE CONTAINER WAS CLEANED OF THE PRODUCT RESIDUE, AND THE LADING PLACED BACK INTO THE ORIGINAL CONTAINER. IT WAS THEN RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT ONTO THE HARBOR FOR VESSEL LOADING.  THE DAMAGED DRUMS ARE TO BE SHIPPED BACK TO THE MANUFACTURER PER THEIR REQUEST.

column168: I OTTO EVANS, LEFT OUR YARD IN HAMMONTON, NJ AT 6:00 A.M., OCTOBER 1, 2002. I ARRIVED AT CYCLE CHEM IN ELIZABETH, NEW JERSEY AT 8:00 A.M. UPON ARRIVAL I CHECKED IN WITH THE LOADING SUPERVISOR (WALTER). WALTER SAID I WOULD NOT BE LOADING THE PRODUCT MYSELF, HE HAD A CREW FOR THAT.  WALTER THEN BEGAN TO ASK PRE-LOADING INSPECTION QUESTIONS. "IS THE TANKER EMPTY?" "YES" I REPLIED. "WHAT ARE THESE PLACARDS?" (1993) "FROM THE LAST LOAD, OILY RINSE WATER", I REPLIED. WALTER CLIMBED ONTO THE CARWALK, OPENED AND INSPECTED THE INSIDE OF THE TANKER AND GAVE HIS MEN THE "O.K." TO BEGAN LOADING. BEFORE THEY BEGAN I ASKED TO SEE THE MANIFEST AND A DRUM LIST. WALTER ID NOT SHOW M A MANIFEST OR A DRUM LIST. STATING THAT IT WAS UNAVAILABLE. I FOLLOWED HIM INSIDE TO FIND OUT WHAT THEY WERE LOADING ONTO MY TANKER. THEY SAID THE LIQUIDS IN THE DRUMS THEY WERE PUMPING ONTO OUR TANKER WERE MILD CORROSIVES CONSISTING OF MIXTURES OF HYDROCHLORIC ACID, SULFURIC ACID, AND A LIST OF OTHERS, BUT WOULD NOT SHOW ME THE LIST.  AFTER ASKING MULTIPLE TIMES. I IMMEDIATELY CALLED MY SUPERVISOR (DAVE ROSELL) AND ADVISED HIM OF THE SITUATION. HE TOLD ME WE ARE THE TRANSPORTER, THEY (CYCLE CHEM) ARE THE SHIPPER, THE GENERATOR AND OUR CUSTOMER JUST DO NOT LEAVE WITHOUT THE PROPER SHIPPING PAPERS. WALTER TOLD ME THAT THE MANIFEST WAS BEING PREPARED WHILE THEY WERE LOADING AND I WOULD HAVE IT IN PLENTY OF TIME BEFORE I WAS TO LEAVE. WHEN I WALKED OUT TO MY TRUCK I OBSERVED TWO MEN FROM CYCLE CHEM WITH ACID SUITS AND FULL-FACE RESPIRATORS ALREADY LOADING OUR TANKER, USING OUR VACUUM TANKERS 2" HOSE AND DROP-TUBE. 132 DRUMS OF LIQUID ONTO MY TRAILER (T306, T-5). AS THEY WERE VACUUMING THE LIQUIDS, I OBSERVED THEM POURING NUMEROUS SMALL CANS, AND CONTAINERS OF ADDITIONAL LIQUIDS INTO THE DRUMS THEY WERE PUMPING FROM. I OBSERVED WALTER PERIODICALLY PUTTING HIS HAND ON THE TANKER. I ASSUME NOW, AFTER THE FACT, THAT HE WAS CHECKING FOR HEAT. THE LOADING PROCESS LASTED FROM 8:00 A.M. TO 12:00 P.M. BEFORE LEAVING, I AGAIN ASKED. WALTER'S ASSISTANT THIS TIME, TO SEE A DRUM LIST.ONCE AGAIN HE SAID IT WAS UNAVAILABLE. AT 12:00 P.M. AS I WAS PULLING OUT OF THE SIDE EXIT OF CYCLE CHEM. OUR TRACTOR SHUT DOWN FROM 12:00 P.M. TO 3:00 P.M. DUE TO WATER IN THE FUEL TWO CYCLE CHEM MECHANICS WORKED ON THE PROBLEM AND AT APPROXIMATELY 3:00 P.M. I LEFT CYCLE CHEM IN ROUTE FOR DUPONT. I ARRIVED AT THE PILOT REST STOP AT EXIT 7 OFF THE NJ TURNPIKE AT 4:30 PM TO EAT AT APPROXIMATELY 5:00 P.M.  PRE-TRIPPED MY TRUCK, WITH SEEMING NORMAL I PROCEEDED DOWN 295 SOUTH. IN THE VICINITY OF EXIT 36-A I HEARD A LOUD BANG AND OBSERVED FUMES AND SMOKE IN THE AIR THAT ALSO FILLED THE CAB OF THE TRUCK. I INSTANTLY EXPERIENCED DIFFICULTY SEEING, BREATHING AND MY THROAT STARTED BURNING. I PULLED OFF TO THE SHOULDER OF THE ROAD. AS SOON AS POSSIBLE, I EXITED THE CAB, MY VISION WAS BLURRY AND I BEGAN TO VOMIT AND STILL HAD DIFFICULTLY BREATHING. AS SOON AS I WAS ABLE I CHECKED THE TANKER AND IT WAS WARM. FUMES WERE COMING FROM
